enced by Darwin's theories, illuminating the surprising continuities between them. Greenwood suggests that it would be neither difficult nor socially dangerous to develop a genuinely evolutionary understanding of human beings, so long as we realized that we could not derive political and moral standards from the study of biological processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHuman evolution. 0aNature and nurture. 0aPhysical anthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aSociobiology. 4aAnthropology. 4aGeneral Science. 4aHistory Of Science. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501719936?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501719936zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501719936/original  a978-3-11-053617-1 Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA